"{\"uid\": \"nzherald.co.nz-nz-politics-government-on-track-for-post-olympic-policy-sprint-luxon-lets-side-down-with-benefit-brain-fade-audrey-young-CMIBG5GYVFAGTB3ZTALOBTGUCE\", \"text\": \"Reminder, this is a Premium article and requires a subscription to read.  Audrey Young is the New Zealand Herald's senior political correspondent. She was named Political Journalist of the Year at the Voyager Media Awards in 2023, 2020 and 2018.  OPINION  This is a transcript of the Premium Politics newsletter. To sign up,clickhere, select Premium Politics Briefing andsave your preferences. For a step-by-step guide,click here.  Welcome to thePoliticsBriefing. Some MPs spendparliamentaryrecesses catching up on electorate work and/or recharging their batteries, but this week's recess has been used by theGovernmentfor some significant announcements, ready to roll out as soon as the Olympics was over.  They were trumped only by theReserve Bank's announcement yesterday thatinterest raterelief is on the way with acut in the Official Cash Rate(OCR) - although it was such a volte-face on its May projections that,as Jen\\u00e9e Tibshraeny put it, it caused whiplash.  Disabilities Minister Louise Upston this morning revealed that thesorry state of Whaikaha - the Ministry of Disabled Peoplewill see it lose the ability to deliver services, which will be transferred to the Ministry of Social Development (MSD). Whaikaha will become more focused on policy and advocacy as a stand-alone agency.  In other announcements, we have seenSimeon Brown pave the way for congestion chargingin conjunction with councils in cities where traffic moves too slowly, and they should be operating before the next election.  It has been talked about for years. Brown is doing something about it, with the caveat that it must be accepted by the public. It has been fairly widely welcomed by the right, who like the concept of user pays, and the left, who want incentives to get people out of cars and on to bikes or public transport.  The objections will come once it is in place from the non-ideological low- and middle-income earners who must travel by car and have no flexibility about the timing of their journeys.  Earlier this week, Upston announcedgreater benefit sanctionsfor the unemployed who do not do the basics required of them by the MSD. Sanctions will kick in when, for example, beneficiaries do not make appointments with their case managers or miss job interviews.  The harshest penalty is a money management card. That will see half of a benefit loaded on to a card for essential spending only. No smokes or booze. It has been condemned as cruel and unfair. Upston makes the point that it is for people who do not meet their basic obligations and there will be warnings first.  Judith Collins has announced the end of the highly restrictive regime preventinggenetic editing and scientific researchthat is normal in most developed countries. That has been met with overwhelming approval by most and cautious reluctance by those who need a little more convincing that it might actually help New Zealand reduce its greenhouse gas emissions through special grasses and fodder and get rid of predators destroying native forests.  Tama Potaka has announced decisions around Te Arawhiti and Te Puni K\\u014dkirithat will reverse the respective powers of the two agencies.  Te Arawhiti, which was the creation of Kelvin Davis in 2018, took over the work of the Office of Treaty Settlements and became an influential agency within government for managing M\\u0101ori-Crown relationships across all of government, including post-settlement relationships.  I well remember the day Te Arawhiti was launched, with invited guest Titewhai Harawira sitting next to then Prime Minister Jacinda Ardern around the Cabinet table where the ceremonies were conducted. Ardern's deputy PM, Winston Peters, avoided conniptions by staying away that day.  The longstanding Ministry of M\\u0101ori Development, Te Puni K\\u014dkiri, fell down the pecking order as Labour gave Te Arawhiti the job of making the public service better Treaty of Waitangi partners. That power imbalance looks set to switch, although the full impact of the changes is not clear. Te Arawhiti will continue the work of Treaty settlements and foreshore and seabed claims, but that is effectively gutting its former roles and transferring its name to the old Office of Treaty Settlements.  Responsibility for post-settlement work will shift to Te Puni K\\u014dkiri. It will have a monitoring role over other Crown agencies and, with its current role overseeing Wh\\u0101nau Ora and a possibly expanded role in social investment, it certainly looks set to supplant Te Arawhiti as the more important agency in dealings on contemporary matters. The knee-jerk response by Opposition parties may be to oppose the move. But Te Puni K\\u014dkiri is better positioned as an operational/ delivery ministry that could be expanded further.  Meanwhile, Shane Jones has had an active recess,putting heat on big power companies over wholesale pricesand kicking off the first of his 15 regional development summits at the top of the South Island, Tauihu.  However, it should not be forgotten that despite his railing against the market-based system set up by Max Bradford in the 1990s, New Zealand First was in Government at time, had the associate energy portfolio and gave it the green light.  Foreign Minister Peters has led a cross-party delegation to the North Pacific, visiting the Marshall Islands, the Federated States of Micronesia and Palau.  \\\"Wh\\u0101ea June was a little different to her two friends though. Mum and Ti, while glamorous and charming like Wh\\u0101ea June, could turn into UFC hitmen if the occasion warranted it.\\\" - Labour MP Willie Jackson's tribute toDame June Mariu, better known as \\\"Aunty June\\\", who died last week, comparing her style to that of his late mother, Dame June Jackson, and veteran activist the late Titewhai Harawira.  Which former MP has been appointed Crown manager to sort out the problems between Wairoa District Council and Hawke's Bay Regional Council over flood protection work? (Answer below.)  Goes to Christopher Luxon for not knowing how much the unemployment benefit was, not even approximately, when asked yesterday by RNZ, and for suggesting on TVNZ that 4000 more MSD staff would become frontline phone case managers when, in fact, 4000 more jobseekers would get case managers.  Goes to theHerald's Jen\\u00e9e Tibshraeny forasking Reserve Bank Governor Adrian Orr the direct question- had he been bluffing in May when he suggested a cut in the OCR might be a year away? Orr denied it, of course, but he may have been bluffing.  Disability shake-up:Disability Issues Minister Louise Upston has announced changes to Whaikaha - the Ministry of Disabled People after a scathing review found it had \\\"no controls\\\" on exploding service costs.  Analysis - OCR cut:Amid the high-fives after the Reserve Bank's surprise OCR cut yesterday, the cynics were reaching for the backs of their necks to soothe the whiplash, writes Jen\\u00e9e Tibshraeny.  GE:Labour and the Greens have given lukewarm responses to moves to make New Zealand's regulatory settings more accommodating of genetic engineering.  Explainer - benefit changes:The Government has this week announced a new \\\"traffic light\\\" system for people receiving the Jobseeker benefit. Here's what you need to know.  Aukus:Former Labour minister Andrew Little has weighed into the Aukus debate, backing the Government's decision to investigate potential New Zealand involvement.  Treaty shift:Te Arawhiti, the Office for M\\u0101ori Crown Relations, will be pared back to focus on negotiating Treaty of Waitangi settlements and Takutai Moana applications.  Congestion charges:The Government is introducing \\\"time-of-use\\\" charges on some of the country's busiest roads, Transport Minister Simeon Brown has announced.  Opinion - Auckland transport:The Government has hinted that it may move to run transport in Auckland. That's unlikely to go down well with Mayor Wayne Brown, writes Simon Wilson.  Death of Dame June Mariu:M\\u0101oridom is mourning after matriarch and advocate Dame Mabel June Hinekahukura Mariu DNZM QSM JP - better known as \\\"Aunty June\\\" - died, aged 92.  Firearms review:The Police Association says it has been deliberately excluded from the consultation processes for proposed firearm law changes and the Prime Minister should intervene.  State house sales:K\\u0101inga Ora sold 167 state houses between 2019 and the beginning of 2024, bringing in more than $80 million in sales.  Emergency housing:The number of households living in emergency housing has been reduced by a third in the last six months, Associate Housing Minister Tama Potaka says.  Quiz answer: Lawrence Yule, a former National MP for Tukituki and a former Hastings Mayor.  For more political news and views, listen toOn the Tiles, theHerald's politics podcast.  Reminder, this is a Premium article and requires a subscription to read.  OPINION: A remarkable exercise in deliberative democracy delivers insights and dignity.\"}"